# Proposed Update — prepare-rebuttal.md

**Source:** SkillTest R2 case-mixed-severity + R4.A case-author-input-needed.
**Status:** Draft only. Do not apply to
`/Users/mjm/MinionsOS/minions/roles/writer/skills/prepare-rebuttal.md` until
the user explicitly approves.

## What to add

The current `prepare-rebuttal.md` covers issue grouping, response-type
classification, evidence coordination via EACN, and honest drafting.
Add the following hard rules under the Procedure section.

### Add Rule: Stable comment IDs (R<N>.C<M>)

> **Label every reviewer comment with a stable ID** of the form
> `R<reviewer-number>.C<comment-number>` (e.g. R1.C2, R2.C1). Use these
> IDs in the response letter, in the revisions checklist, in EACN tasks,
> and in commit messages. Do NOT label by paraphrased prose ("the
> reviewer's third concern about the GPU acceleration question") because
> identical paraphrases creep across letters and break the cross-link.

Evidence: SkillTest R2 case-mixed-severity. Stable IDs let the editor,
the rebuttal author, the experimenter, and the citation auditor all
refer to the same thing without rebuilding the mapping every time.

### Add Rule: Action-label FSM per comment

> **Classify every comment with an explicit action label**, not prose
> mood. Allowed labels (composite allowed where applicable):
> - `ACCEPT_TEXT` — concession by edit.
> - `ACCEPT_ANALYSIS` — concession by added analysis on existing data.
> - `ACCEPT_EXPERIMENT` — concession by new experiment / new data.
> - `ACCEPT_FIGURE` — concession by figure regeneration / addition.
> - `ADD_CITATION` — missing-citation fix.
> - `SOFTEN_CLAIM` — narrow scope, hedge, or qualify.
> - `DISAGREE_WITH_JUSTIFICATION` — hold the line, justify with
>   citation or derivation.
> - `PARTIAL` — accept part, disagree with part.
> - `AUTHOR_INPUT_NEEDED` — author position is partial / unconfirmed
>   and the response cannot be drafted without further author input.
>
> Composite labels (`DISAGREE + SOFTEN`, `ACCEPT_EXPERIMENT + SOFTEN_CLAIM`)
> are allowed when one comment legitimately spans two responses.

Evidence: SkillTest R2 + R4.A. The full FSM is empirically exercised
across both rounds (10 distinct comment archetypes, no orphan archetype).

### Add Rule: AUTHOR_INPUT_NEEDED flag at top of letter

> **When ANY comment is `AUTHOR_INPUT_NEEDED`, flag this in the
> opening paragraph of the response letter** (visible to the editor on
> first read). Do NOT bury unresolved-author-input flags inside the
> per-comment section — editors triage cover letters; an unresolved
> point hidden in the body is a submission-quality failure.

Evidence: SkillTest R4.A case-author-input-needed. Baseline buried
2-of-4 unresolved comments inside the comment-by-comment section;
candidate flagged this in the cover-letter opening. Editor experience
on a real submission would catch the flag immediately rather than
discovering it mid-read.

### Add Rule: PI question list as a separate section

> **For any `AUTHOR_INPUT_NEEDED` comment, emit 2-4 specific questions
> the corresponding author can paste into an email to the PI** as a
> dedicated section at the end of the response packet. Status updates
> ("R2.C1 remains unresolved until the PI confirms whether GPU
> acceleration was attempted") are NOT acceptable substitutes — the
> author needs an actionable question to send.

Evidence: SkillTest R4.A. Baseline produced status updates only;
candidate emitted 6 specific questions (3 per unresolved comment) as a
separate "Questions for the PI" section.

### Add Rule: `[X]` placeholder discipline

> **Use `[X]` placeholders (or `[page/line/section X]`) for
> manuscript locations the rebuttal author cannot verify at draft
> time.** Do NOT fabricate page numbers ("page 12, lines 310-324")
> when the manuscript hasn't been recompiled with the rebuttal edits.
> The placeholder gets filled at the apply-revisions stage when the
> compiled PDF is in hand.

Evidence: SkillTest R2 case-mixed-severity. Baseline fabricated
specific page / line numbers; candidate used `[X]` and `[page/line]`
placeholders. Fabricated locations break the editor's spot-check.

### Add Rule: Disagreement pattern (acknowledge → narrow → justify → soften)

> **For any `DISAGREE_WITH_JUSTIFICATION`, follow the pattern:**
> 1. Acknowledge the reviewer's concern in their own framing.
> 2. Narrow the disagreement to a specific sub-claim.
> 3. Justify with citation, derivation, or experimental evidence.
> 4. Soften the residual claim if the justification is partial.
>
> A bare "we disagree because [reason]" without acknowledgement reads
> as defensive; a bare acknowledgement without justification reads as
> capitulation.

Evidence: SkillTest R2. Composite `DISAGREE + SOFTEN` was the
candidate's most successful response shape on borderline reviewer
asks.

## What to leave unchanged

- The issue-grouping discipline (cluster by topic, rank by severity +
  breadth, top priority = shared concerns).
- The EACN coordination rule (open targeted task to Experimenter or
  Expert with exact question + deadline).
- The honesty audit (no "will do in camera-ready" promises the team
  cannot deliver, no silent scope expansion).
- The pitfalls list.

## Why these are the right additions

R2 + R4.A cross-validate every rule:

| Rule | R2 evidence | R4.A evidence |
|---|---|---|
| Stable IDs | +1 dim | +1 dim |
| Action labels (full FSM) | 6 archetypes | 4 archetypes (incl. AUTHOR_INPUT_NEEDED) |
| Top-of-letter unresolved flag | n/a | +2 dims (decisive) |
| PI question list | n/a | +2 dims |
| `[X]` placeholders | +2 dims | confirmed |
| Disagreement pattern | confirmed | confirmed |

Every rule has evidence from at least one round; the high-leverage
ones (action labels, top-of-letter flag) are independently confirmed.
